## The Role of U.S. Oil Production

The U.S. is the world's largest oil producer, contributing about 20% of global output:

- **Shale Oil Boom:** Technological advances in hydraulic fracturing have significantly increased U.S. production since 2014, challenging OPEC's market dominance ([McFarlane, 2022](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/o/opec.asp)).

- **Production Constraints:** Despite high prices, U.S. producers have been cautious in expanding output due to capital discipline, regulatory policies, and environmental considerations ([Nereim, 2021](https://www.npr.org/2021/07/07/1013700207/oil-prices-are-in-turmoil-right-now-heres-what-you-need-to-know)).

- **Political and Environmental Factors:** The Biden administration's focus on reducing fossil fuel reliance and climate change mitigation has created political headwinds for rapid production increases ([Jacobson, 2021](https://www.politifact.com/article/2021/nov/04/why-are-oil-prices-so-high-and-what-can-be-done-abou/)).

